 {"id":"DIAL-fse","title":"Battery level monitoring with low-battery notifications","description":"# Description

Implement battery level monitoring for the Surface Dial, exposing battery percentage in status commands and triggering low-battery notifications.

## Background & Rationale

### The Problem
The Surface Dial is a battery-powered Bluetooth device. Currently:
- Users have NO way to know the battery level
- The dial simply stops working when the battery dies
- This leads to frustrating "why isn't it working?" moments
- Users can't proactively replace/charge batteries

### Why This Matters
1. **Prevents unexpected failures** — Know before the dial dies
2. **Professional expectation** — All wireless devices show battery (mice, keyboards, AirPods)
3. **Proactive maintenance** — Replace batteries during natural breaks
4. **Debugging aid** — "Is it the battery?" is a common support question
5. **Trust building** — Tool that cares about user experience

### Technical Background
The Surface Dial, like most HID devices, reports battery level via the standard HID Battery System page (0x85). The battery level is typically available as a percentage (0-100) or a charging state enum.

HID Report Descriptor typically includes:
- Usage Page: 0x85 (Battery System)
- Usage: 0x44 (RemainingCapacity) - percentage
- Usage: 0x45 (FullChargeCapacity)
- Usage: 0x66 (GoodRun) or 0x67 (ConditioningFlag)

## Implementation Details

### Reading Battery Level

```rust
// src/battery.rs

use hidapi::HidDevice;

/// Battery level and charging state
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, serde::Serialize)]
pub struct BatteryStatus {
    /// Battery percentage (0-100), None if unavailable
    pub percent: Option<u8>,
    /// Whether the device is currently charging
    pub charging: bool,
    /// Estimated minutes remaining, if available
    pub minutes_remaining: Option<u32>,
}

impl BatteryStatus {
    /// Read battery status from HID device
    ///
    /// Surface Dial reports battery via HID feature report.
    /// Report format varies by firmware version.
    pub fn read(device: &HidDevice) -> Option<Self> {
        // Try to read battery feature report
        // Report ID for battery is typically 0x05 or found via descriptor parsing
        let mut buf = [0u8; 8];

        // Send get-feature request for battery report
        match device.get_feature_report(&mut buf) {
            Ok(len) if len >= 2 => {
                // Parse battery percentage from report
                // Format: [report_id, battery_percent, charging_flag?, ...]
                let percent = buf[1].min(100);
                let charging = len > 2 && (buf[2] & 0x01) != 0;

                Some(BatteryStatus {
                    percent: Some(percent),
                    charging,
                    minutes_remaining: None,
                })
            }
            _ => None,
        }
    }

    /// Check if battery is low (below threshold)
    pub fn is_low(&self, threshold: u8) -> bool {
        self.percent.map(|p| p <= threshold).unwrap_or(false)
    }

    /// Check if battery is critical (below 10%)
    pub fn is_critical(&self) -> bool {
        self.is_low(10)
    }
}
